es towards higher redshifts, with \emph{{$\alpha<$}i/{$>$} decreasing from -1.47\textsuperscript{+0.02{$<$}sup/{$>$}\textsubscript{-0.02{$<$}sub/{$>$} at \emph{z{$<$}i/{$>$} {$\simeq$} 0.1 to -2.11\textsuperscript{+0.30{$<$}sup/{$>$}\textsubscript{-0.13{$<$}sub/{$>$} at \emph{z{$<$}i/{$>$} {$\simeq$} 5. This slope depends on the characterisation of the observational uncertainties, which is crucial to properly remove the Eddington bias. We show that there is currently no consensus on the method to quantify such errors: different error models result in different best-fit Schechter parameters.}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}}},
